<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-derivative-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Introduction and Motivation for Derivatives</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Describe average rate of change and interpret it as a secant slope.
      </li>
      <li>
        Explain instantaneous velocity as a limit of average velocities.
      </li>
      <li>
        Connect instantaneous rate of change to the slope of a tangent line.
      </li>
      <li>
        Estimate an instantaneous rate of change using tables and nearby average rates.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>
    Derivatives begin with a simple question: how fast is something changing <emph>right now</emph>?
    You already know how to compute an <emph>average</emph> rate of change over a time interval.
    The derivative is what happens when we shrink that interval smaller and smaller and look at the limiting behavior.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="instantaneous-velocity">
    <title>Instantaneous Velocity</title>

    <p>
      Suppose a particle moves along a line so that at time <m>t</m> it is at position <m>f(t)</m>.
      Over the time interval from <m>t=a</m> to <m>t=b</m>, the change in position is <m>f(b)-f(a)</m>,
      so the average velocity is
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle v_{\text{avg}}=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Instantaneous velocity at time <m>t=a</m> is not computed from a single moment.
      Instead, we look at the average velocity from <m>a</m> to <m>a+h</m> and then take a limit as <m>h\to 0</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle v=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}.
    </me>

    <remark xml:id="rem-velocity-speed">
      <p>
        Velocity can be positive or negative depending on direction. Speed is the absolute value of velocity.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="ex-falling-stone">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A stone dropped from a bridge has position (in feet below the bridge) approximately
          <m>f(t)=16t^2</m> after <m>t</m> seconds.
        </p>
        <p>
          (a) Compute the average velocity on <m>[3,4]</m>.
          (b) Estimate the instantaneous velocity at <m>t=3</m> using a table of average velocities.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          (a) The average velocity from <m>t=3</m> to <m>t=4</m> is
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle v_{\text{avg}}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{f(4)-f(3)}{4-3}
\\[0.8em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{16(4^2)-16(3^2)}{1}
\\[0.8em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 112.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          (b) To estimate the instantaneous velocity at <m>t=3</m>, compute the average velocity from <m>3</m> to <m>3+h</m>
          for smaller and smaller values of <m>h</m>.
        </p>

        <table xml:id="tab-falling-stone-avg-vel">
          <caption>Average velocity from <m>t=3</m> to <m>t=3+h</m> for <m>f(t)=16t^2</m>.</caption>
          <tabular>
            <row header="yes">
              <cell><m>h</m></cell>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.01</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.001</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.0001</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.00001</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>v_{\text{avg}}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>112</m></cell>
              <cell><m>97.6</m></cell>
              <cell><m>96.16</m></cell>
              <cell><m>96.016</m></cell>
              <cell><m>96.0016</m></cell>
              <cell><m>96.00016</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>
          The values approach <m>96</m>, so we define the instantaneous velocity at <m>t=3</m> to be <m>96</m> ft/sec.
          We can also verify this by simplifying the average velocity algebraically.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle v_{\text{avg}}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{(3+h)-3}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{16(3+h)^2-16(3^2)}{h}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16\cdot\frac{(3+h)^2-3^2}{h}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16\cdot\frac{(9+6h+h^2)-9}{h}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16\cdot\frac{6h+h^2}{h}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16(6+h)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 96+16h.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Taking the limit as <m>h\to 0</m> gives
          <m>\displaystyle v=\lim_{h\to 0}(96+16h)=96</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="secant-and-tangent">
    <title>Secant Slopes and Tangent Slopes</title>

    <p>
      There is also a geometric interpretation. The slope of a secant line through
      <m>(a,f(a))</m> and <m>(b,f(b))</m> is
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle m_{\text{sec}}=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This is the same formula as the average rate of change. When <m>b=a+h</m>, the secant slope is
      <m>\displaystyle \frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}</m>.
      As <m>h\to 0</m>, the secant line approaches the tangent line at <m>x=a</m>, and the secant slopes approach the tangent slope.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-secant-to-tangent">
      <caption>
        Secant lines approaching a tangent line as the second point moves toward <m>x=a</m>.
      </caption>
      <image width="90%" xml:id="secant-tangent-tikz">
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The tangent slope at <m>x=a</m> is the limit of the secant slopes:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle m=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This is the same limit that defines instantaneous velocity, which is why derivatives describe both slopes on graphs and rates of change in applications.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="temperature-model">
    <title>A Trigonometric Model and Estimating Rates</title>

    <p>
      Derivatives are also used to interpret how quickly a modeled quantity is changing.
      For example, suppose the average daily temperature over a year is modeled by
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle T(x)=55-40\cos\!\left(\frac{2\pi}{365}x\right),
      \quad\text{degrees F on day } x.
    </me>

    <example xml:id="ex-temperature-average-rates">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Estimate how quickly the weather is warming at <m>x=100</m> (about April 10) in degrees/day.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We approximate the instantaneous rate of change at <m>x=100</m> using nearby average rates.
          For example, on the interval <m>[100,110]</m>,
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle r_1
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{T(110)-T(100)}{110-100}
\\[1.1em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{\bigl(55-40\cos(\frac{2\pi}{365}\cdot 110)\bigr)-\bigl(55-40\cos(\frac{2\pi}{365}\cdot 100)\bigr)}{10}
\\[1.1em]
\amp\approx\amp \displaystyle 0.668.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          On the interval <m>[90,100]</m>, we similarly get an estimate <m>r_2\approx 0.686</m>.
          A reasonable estimate for the instantaneous rate is the average of these two:
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle r\approx \frac{1}{2}(r_1+r_2)\approx 0.677.
        </me>

        <p>
          Interpreting this in context, the model predicts warming of about <m>0.7</m> degrees F per day near day <m>100</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <figure xml:id="fig-temperature-model">
      <caption>
        A sinusoidal temperature model. Near a chosen day, a nearby secant slope estimates the instantaneous rate of change.
      </caption>
      <image width="90%" xml:id="temperature-model-tikz">
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      In the next sections, we will turn these ideas into a precise definition and learn techniques for computing derivatives efficiently.
    </p>
  </subsection>

</section>
